    "intro": "AUTOSAR (AUTomotive Open System ARchitecture) is a worldwide development partnership of automotive interested parties that has established an open and standardized software architecture for automotive electronic control units (ECUs). It provides a scalable and flexible framework for managing the growing complexity of automotive software.",
    "sections": [
        {
            "title": "The SWC Runnable: Heart of App Logic",
            "text": "In AUTOSAR, the actual logic resides in Software Components (SWCs). Runnables are the periodic or event-driven functions that execute this logic, triggered by the Runtime Environment (RTE).",
            "code": {
                "lang": "C (AUTOSAR Runnable)",
                "content": "// Example: Periodic Runnable for a Headlight Controller\n#include \"Rte_HeadlightControl.h\"\n\nvoid Runnable_HeadlightControl_10ms(void) {\n    uint8 lightStatus;\n    uint8 switchInput;\n\n    // Read input data from RTE Port\n    (void)Rte_Read_rpLightSwitch_Element(&switchInput);\n\n    if(switchInput == 1) {\n        lightStatus = 1; // ON\n    } else {\n        lightStatus = 0; // OFF\n    }\n\n    // Write output data to RTE Port\n    (void)Rte_Write_ppLightStatus_Element(lightStatus);\n}"
            },
            "info": "The RTE (Runtime Environment) is the glue that connects SWCs to the BSW and each other, ensuring hardware independence for the application software."
        },
        {
            "title": "Classic vs. Adaptive Platform",
            "list": [
                "Classic Platform: For deeply embedded ECUs with real-time and safety constraints (OSEK/VDX based).",
                "Adaptive Platform: For high-performance computing units (HPCUs) like ADAS and Infotainment (POSIX/C++ based).",
                "Interoperability: Both platforms can coexist in a vehicle through Signal-based and Service-oriented communication."
            ]
        }
    ],
